SIMPLE: location
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Location
<hw>Lo*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>locatio</ets>, fr. <ets>locare</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
act or process of locating.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Situation; place; locality.</def>
<rj><au>Locke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is located; a tract of land designated in
place.</def> <mark>[U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Civil Law)</fld>
<def>A leasing on rent.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Scots Law)</fld> <def>A
contract for the use of a thing, or service of a person, for hire.</def>
<au>Wharton.</au> <sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Amer. Law)</fld> <def>The marking
out of the boundaries, or identifying the place or site of, a piece of
land, according to the description given in an entry, plan, map,
etc.</def> <rj><au>Burrill. Bouvier.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Locative</ent>⟦br⟧
